                                          2530  # Instruction SYS: Native call, <=256 cycles (<=128 ticks, in reality less)
                                          2531  #
                                          2532  # The 'SYS' vCPU instruction first checks the number of desired ticks given by
                                          2533  # the operand. As long as there are insufficient ticks available in the current
                                          2534  # time slice, the instruction will be retried. This will effectively wait for
                                          2535  # the next scan line if the current slice is almost out of time. Then a jump to
                                          2536  # native code is made. This code can do whatever it wants, but it must return
                                          2537  # to the 'REENTER' label when done. When returning, AC must hold (the negative
                                          2538  # of) the actual consumed number of whole ticks for the entire virtual
                                          2539  # instruction cycle (from NEXT to NEXT). This duration may not exceed the prior
                                          2540  # declared duration in the operand + 28 (or maxTicks). The operand specifies the
                                          2541  # (negative) of the maximum number of *extra* ticks that the native call will
                                          2542  # need. The GCL compiler automatically makes this calculation from gross number
                                          2543  # of cycles to excess number of ticks.
                                          2544  # SYS functions can modify vPC to implement repetition. For example to split
                                          2545  # up work into multiple chucks.
                                          2546  label('SYS')
SYS:          03b4 8115  adda [$15]       2547  adda([vTicks])                  #10
              03b5 e8c8  blt  .sys#13     2548  blt('.sys#13')                  #11
              03b6 1523  ld   [$23],y     2549  ld([sysFn+1],Y)                 #12
              03b7 e122  jmp  y,[$22]     2550  jmp(Y,[sysFn])                  #13
